08204nam a22011535i 9783110675498DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021941715  a97831106754987 a10.1515/97831106754982doi  a(DE-B1597)536001  a(OCoLC)1284999228  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aBP55 7aREL0410002bisacsh04a297.0922304aThe Study of Islamic Origins :bNew Perspectives and Contexts /ced. by Mette Bjerregaard Mortensen, Guillaume Dye, Isaac W. Oliver, Tommaso Tesei. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (VI, 376 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJudaism, Christianity, and Islam – Tension, Transmission, Transformation ,x2196-405X ;v1500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tI Early Islam and the Qur’ān: Methodological Considerations -- tThe Current Status and Problems of Islamic Origins -- tA New Arabic Apocryphon from Late Antiquity: The Qurʾān -- tII Early Islam and the Qur’ān: Historical, Literary, and Cross-Comparative Analyses -- tBody Parts Nomenclature in the Qur’anic Corpus -- tThe Queen of Sheba in the Qur’ān and Late Antique Midrash -- tStanding under the Mountain: Jewish and Christian Threads to a Qur’anic Construction -- tMapping the Sources of the Qur’anic Jesus -- tThe Natural Theology of the Qur’ān and Its Late Antique Christian Background: A Preliminary Outline -- tIII Early Islam and the Qur’ān: Social, Political, and Religious Contexts -- tQ 2:102, 43:31, and Ctesiphon-Seleucia -- tProphecies Fulfilled: The Qur’anic Arabs in the Early 600s -- tThe Sasanian Conquest of Ḥimyar Reconsidered: In Search of a Local Hero -- tContextual Readings of Religious Statements in Early Islamic Inscriptions -- tThe Gods of the Qur’ān: The Rise of Ḥijāzī Henotheism during Late Antiquity -- t“One Community to the Exclusion of Other People”: A Superordinate Identity in the Medinan Community -- tList of Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe study of Islam’s origins from a rigorous historical and social science perspective is still wanting. At the same time, a renewed attention is being paid to the very plausible pre-canonical redactional and editorial stages of the Qur'an, a book whose core many contemporary scholars agree to be formed by various independent writings in which encrypted passages from the OT Pseudepigrapha, the NT Apocrypha, and other ancient writings of Jewish, Christian, and Manichaean provenance may be found. Likewise, the earliest Islamic community is presently regarded by many scholars as a somewhat undetermined monotheistic group that evolved from an original Jewish-Christian milieu into a distinct Muslim group perhaps much later than commonly assumed and in a rather unclear way. The following volume gathers select studies that were originally shared at the Early Islamic Studies Seminar. These studies aim at exploring afresh the dawn and early history of Islam with the tools of biblical criticism as well as the approaches set forth in the study of Second Temple Judaism, Christian, and Rabbinic origins, thereby contributing to the renewed, interdisciplinary study of formative Islam as part and parcel of the complex processes of religious identity formation during Late Antiquity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aIslamxHistory. 0aIslamxOrigin. 0aIslamxSocial aspects. 4aIslam. 4aKoran. 4aProphet Mohammed. 4aSpätantike. 7aRELIGION / Islam / Koran & Sacred Writings.2bisacsh  aIslam.  aLate Antiquity.  aMuhammad.  aQuran.1 aBjerregaard Mortensen, Mette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBjerregaard Mortensen, Mette, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov